    <h1 class="opener__hed  -is-over-bg opener__hed--light opener__hed--small" >        Segregation Academies Still Operate Across the South. One Town Grapples With Its Divided Schools.
    </h1>

    
            <div class="article-meta-1  -is-over-bg article-meta-1--light">
            <span class="article-meta-1__byline">
                by <a class="name" href="https://www.propublica.org/people/jennifer-berry-hawes">Jennifer Berry Hawes</a>            </span>
            <time class="article-meta-1__pubdate">
                <time class="timestamp" datetime="2024-05-18EDT05:00">May 18, 5 a.m. EDT</time>
            </time>
        </div>
    
    </div> <!-- Close .opener__topic-title-dek-wrapper -->

        <div class="content"> <!-- not sure if this is the best way to reestablish the text column -->
        <h2 class="opener__dek opener__dek--match-text-column" >            Seventy years after Brown v. Board, Black and white residents, in Camden, Alabama, say they would like to see their children schooled together. But after so long apart, they aren’t sure how to make it happen.
        </h2>
    </div>
    
</div>
        
<div class="article-meta-1
     article-meta-1--left      article-meta-1--hide-byline " data-pp-location="article meta">

    <span class="article-meta-1__byline" data-pp-location="article byine">
        by <a class="name" href="https://www.propublica.org/people/jennifer-berry-hawes">Jennifer Berry Hawes</a>    </span>
    <time class="article-meta-1__pubdate">
        <time class="timestamp" datetime="2024-05-18EDT05:00">May 18, 5 a.m. EDT</time>
    </time>

